defaultQ57 default&#xa0; 
default 
defaultThe Chairman:default Good afternoon.
default 
defaultI think you were sitting at the back listening and you will pretty well know ho
defaultw these things proceed.
default 
defaultYou are extremely welcome here, first of all, Mr Parker, from
default the NFU, and Mr Hale and Mr Kr
defaultó
defaultl from the Alternative Investment Management Association.
default 
defaultThe questions will be pretty obvious.
default 
defaultSome are directed to the NFU and some to you, but if you feel that you have something to contribute to the answers, please come in and say so; on the other hand, if you agree with what is being said, I do not think there is any point in saying it a second or third time.
defaultWe will start.
default 
defaultI will ask the first question, and I will ask the Lord Wrigglesworth to ask the second question.
default 
defaultThis one is quite clearly to Mr Parker, originally: could you give us an overview of why businesses are set up as partnerships in the agricultural sector?
default 
defaultWhat types of partnerships are used and what are the implications for the sector of the clauses in the draft Finance Bill?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: By way of background, in excess of 90% of farm businesses are unincorporated.
default 
defaultProbably in the region of 40% trade through a partnership.
default 
defaultPrimarily, that is through a general partnership.
default 
defaultThere is very little use of LLPs in our industry.
default 
defaultThe partnership structure is a particularly suitable one for farming businesses, which tend to be family businesses, often intergenerational and with several generations included within the same partnership.
default 
defaultIt is quite a simple structure to operate through.
default 
defaultThere is less formality compared to a limited company and it probably provides greater flexibility in terms of rewarding different partners for their changing contributions to the partnership over a long career.
default 
defaultAlso, perhaps some of the benefits of limited companies are not necessarily relevant.
default 
defaultThey are not necessarily looking to offer equity to external investors and there may be limited need for a limited liability.
default 
defaultThere are some mixed partnerships, as I think has been alluded to in earlier evidence from other people.
default 
defaultOften, that is for a commercial reason or an historic reason; some of these have existed for many years.
default 
defaultIn some cases, there are land-tenure issues as to why you would not fully incorporate a business.
default 
defaultThat is pretty much my overview.
defaultThe Chairman:default What is the effect of the draft clauses in the Finance Bill on the agricultural sector?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: It is primarily the mixed-partnership legislation that could have an impact.
default 
defaultIt is really dependent on how the legislation is interpreted.
default 
defaultWe have gone from original proposals, which seemed to have a motive test that one of the main reasons for the business structure was tax avoidance, to something which is more around whether it is reasonable to assume that a tax advantage has been arrived at.
default 
defaultIt really depends upon how the legislation is interpreted on mixed partnerships.
defaultThe Chairman:default Can you give examples of where you think the proposals would be damaging to agriculture?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: It creates uncertainty.
default 
defaultIf you have a mixed partnership with a corporate partner in it, you are potentially within the legislation.
default 
defaultYou will have to justify what the corporate member is doing in return for the profit allocation, and that leaves you open to having to incur costs and advice, and justifying that, even in purely commercial arrangements.
defaultQ58 default&#xa0; 
default 
defaultLord Wrigglesworth:default Do you accept that structures involving partnerships in businesses are being used for tax-avoidance purposes?
default 
defaultHow should the Government attack tax avoidance if some structures are being used for that purpose?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: Yes, I accept that there are some that will be using this business structure in that way.
default 
defaultIt depends a little on how you define tax avoidance: whether you define that as lost tax or whether you include deferral of tax on profits.
default 
defaultThere has been mention of some businesses seeking to retain profits for working capital and there has also been talk about disparity between income tax rates and corporation tax rates.
default 
defaultIt rather depends on what we are talking about there.
default 
defaultIf we are talking about tax lost, I would perfectly agree with that.
default 
defaultUnfortunately, this legislation includes even deferral, where there is not going to be tax loss because, when the profits are extracted, higher-rate tax will be due.
default 
defaultThere is a potential issue there.
defaultLord Wrigglesworth:default Do you think that the current proposals are weighted too much towards counter-avoidance and do not pay enough care and attention to the business case for it?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: They are fairly widely drawn, so that they do, perhaps, have the potential to limit a business’s ability to retain and invest profits.
default 
defaultWe have seen the gap between corporation tax and income tax rates widen.
default 
defaultWe have seen, certainly in farming, agricultural buildings allowances abolished and we have seen reductions in capital allowances, and farming is particularly capital intensive, which makes it far more difficult to continue to invest at the same level.
default 
defaultThat is not to say that that is the reason why the majority of mixed partnerships exist in farming.
default 
defaultThe majority are commercially driven and historic where land ownership has been fragmented, or land tenure, in some cases.
defaultQ59 default&#xa0; 
default 
defaultBaroness Drake:default I come to the issue of the tests proposed in the draft legislation for determining whether partnership profits or losses can be reallocated by the HMRC.
default 
defaultMr Parker, starting with you, the farmers’ group submission stated that the proposed tests are extremely subjective and, as a result, are not well targeted.
default 
defaultPerhaps you could elaborate on why you think they are not sufficiently targeted.
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: The original statement seemed to suggest that it would not affect businesses where the driver for the structure was commercial.
default 
defaultIt potentially does now or, at the very least, it will mean you have to justify what the corporate partner’s role in the business is and whether the profit that it receives is commensurate with what it brings to the partnership.
defaultBaroness Drake:default There are four specific criteria, but are they equally untargeted in your view or are there particular ones within those four?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: I would have preferred to have seen a tax-motive test as the first thing as to whether the legislation should apply to the business.
default 
defaultThat is one of the main issues, because it brings uncertainty.
default 
defaultAs I said, in the majority of cases, the profit share would be justified, but it is potentially going to be necessary to do that.
defaultBaroness Drake:default If the company’s share of the partnership profits 
defaultis
default not excessive, will they not be safe?
defaultMichael Parkerdefault: Yes, it would only be if they were judged to be excessive.
default 
defaultThat leaves quite a lot open to debate in terms of what a realistic return for that business is and what that business brings to the partnership.
defaultBaroness Drake:default Do other members of the panel want to comment on that particular provision?
defaultPaul Haledefault: The same issues are relevant to partnerships operating in a wide variety of businesses.
default 
defaultIn each case, there is going to be an issue in identifying whether the reward to the corporate member, which, on the face of it, in the legislation, is couched in terms of a return on money at interest equal to the amount of capital that the corporate entity is putting into the business, is excessive or not.
default 
defaultThere are going to be questions on what the appropriate rate of return is.
default 
defaultIt is introducing a lot of uncertainty into businesses where there is no excessive tax-avoidance motive.
default 
defaultThere may be what the Government clearly is trying to regard as some form of tax-avoidance motive, in that you try to accumulate working capital for the business in a form that attracts corporation tax at 20%-odd rather than personal income taxes.
default 
defaultYou can have a big debate over whether that is tax avoidance or acceptable tax mitigation.
defaultQ60 default&#xa0; 
defaultLord Bilimoria:default Just following on from that, could you give us an overview of the role of partnerships in the sector that your association represents, Mr 
defaultKról
default and Mr Hale, and the relevance of the Finance Bill?
defaultPaul Haledefault: Would it be helpful if I just gave you a little bit of background about AIMA?
defaultLord Bilimoria:default Yes, please.
defaultPaul Haledefault: That will then lead into some of the questions, and certainly some of the ones that you were putting to the accountancy bodies earlier.
default 
defaultBy way of background, AIMA is the global trade association for the hedge fund industry.
default 
defaultIts role is to provide leadership to the industry and it represents all of the practitioners.
default 
defaultThat includes hedge fund managers, fund of hedge fund managers, prime brokers, legal and accounting firms, investors, fund administrators and independent fund directors.
default 
defaultWe have more than 1,400 corporate members in over 50 countries and are represented in all of the major financial centres globally.
default 
defaultManager members account for approximately $1.3 trillion, which is roughly 
default50% of the worldwide hedge fund industry’s assets under management.
default 
defaultThat is our global position.
default 
defaultOur members in the 
defaultUK
default represent about 28% of the entire membership, and we have currently 395 UK-based members.
default 
default67% of those—two thirds or about 260—are managers.
default 
defaultThey collectively manage somewhere between $500 billion and $700 billion of assets.
default 
defaultWe believe that about 60% of those 263 managers are established as LLPs, with perhaps a handful as a limited or general partnership, so this legislation is very relevant to our members.
defaultThere are some further background details, which I will give you very briefly, because they are definitely relevant to the matters you are considering.
default 
defaultThese managers carry on the business of investment managers; that is, they manage investments held by funds, the shares or interests in which are marketed to investors, or else they manage institutional managed accounts for insurance companie
defaults and pension funds et cetera
default.
default 
defaultThe managers do not, themselves, hold monies or assets, which is the role in the structure of prime brokers, depositaries or custodians, and the managers are not funds themselves.
default 
defaultThey are regulated by the FCA.
default 
defaultUnder the Alternative Investment Fund Managers Directive, which is coming into force, many, if not all, of these asset managers will be classed as alternative investment fund managers, and the funds they manage as alternative investment funds—these are often referred to by the lovely acronyms AIFMs and AIFs.
default 
defaultThis means that the managers will be potentially subject to the regime imposed under the AIFMD on variable remuneration, which will require that receipt of a significant proportion of variable remuneration must be deferred.
default 
defaultThat will be between 40% and 60% of variable remuneration—in most cases, we believe it will be 60%—with at least a three-year or up to a five-year, perhaps, deferral period.
default 
defaultHalf of all variable remuneration, whether received up front or deferred, will have to be received in the form of equity interests—in practice, equity in the fund—and that must be retained for at least six months.
defaultThe AIFMD is in the process of coming into effect but many managers are already operating similar deferment regimes for business reasons, not least because there are investor pressures.
default 
defaultEven if the managers are not required under the rules in the directive to operate this deferral regime, because they pass a series of proportionality tests, they may fall into other regimes under other directives or under voluntary arrangements, which will require them to operate these deferral arrangements.
defaultThe consequence is that, in these Finance Bill proposals, the parts that are of relevance to our members are those on the position of salaried members of LLPs, those which relate to the allocation of profits within partnerships with mixed membership, and, in particular, the provision that you were discussing earlier with the accountancy bodies, which relate to AIFM businesses.
default 
defaultThat part of the schedule is an easement—it is not a tax-raising provision at all—and is being developed with a considerable amount of input from our organisation to provide a solution to a problem that arises because of the AIFMD deferral regime.
default 
defaultWe are happy to talk further on that to a specific question, if you wish.
defaultJiří Króldefault: The AIFMD is currently being implemented in the EU and the 
defaultUK
default.
default 
defaultSome of the uncertainties that previous speakers have mentioned as it relates to remuneration or profit shares have become doubly more complex, because rules on remuneration under th
defaulte AIFMD itself are not quite clear as to whether profit shares count or not as remuneration or as profit shares.
default 
defaultThat goes for various forms of management companies.
default 
defaultSo there is an extra, added complexity for managers who are now preparing to implement AIFMD as well as preparing for the changes that this legislation is likely to bring.
defaultQ61 default&#xa0; 
defaultLord Bilimoria:default If I may just build on this and ask some really specific questions, you have said very clearly that you have a particular interest in the changes that will affect the AIFM sector.
default 
defaultTo what extent were you involved in discussing the proposals with HMRC subsequent to the issue of the consultative document in May 2013?
defaultPaul Haledefault: Very considerably.
default 
defaultIn the period from early June to the end of September, we had, I think, three substantial meetings of two hours or more with a considerable team of HMRC, HMT and FCA representatives.
default 
defaultWe had a telephone conversation as well, which was a good hour or so, and a considerable amount of email correspondence.
default 
defaultThat resulted in the development of what is now the AIFM business part of the schedule.
defaultLord Bilimoria:default It seems that the pronounced effect on the firms in your sector came as a surprise to HMRC.
default 
defaultIs that correct?
default 
defaultDid they listen to the points that you made on behalf of the sector?
default 
defaultAre you satisfied with the outcome?
defaultPaul Haledefault: It should not have been a surprise to HMT, HMRC and the FCA, because the very point had been identified in submissions made to the FCA in relation to the introduction of the AIFMD.
default 
defaultIt had been made in liaison meetings with HMT and HMRC, and I am afraid to say that the right channels of communication, quite clearly, had not been present.
default 
defaultThat was over a period of, perhaps, a year to 18 months prior to the consultative document coming out.
defaultTo give, following that brickbat, very much credit, though, to HMRC, HMT and the FCA, when we went to our first meeting with them, the atmosphere and the attitude that they had changed very rapidly when they realised that we had a valid point and one that needed to be addressed.
default 
defaultIt was perhaps sealed when we described the point, which, effectively, is that, if the deferral has to be made of the whole of the remuneration—the 100% of variable—the manager who has been lucky enough to receive this amount of money has, perhaps, 20% in cash and 20% of that amount in fund equities, which he cannot redeem for six months, but he has a tax bill equal to 47% of that amount, which is due in approximately a year’s time—maybe less.
default 
defaultFurther, if he loses remuneration, he still has the tax bill.
default 
defaultWhen the FCA representative confirmed, more or less with the one-word answer “
defaultYes
default”, when HMRC asked “Is that a correct interpretation of the effects of the deferral rules?”, there was a considerable amount of willingness to find a solution to this.
default 
defaultThe effort spent on this must have been a considerable part of the workload of Richard Rogers at HMRC and his team over those few months.
default 
defaultIn that sense, yes, we made the point and it was listened to, but I am afraid it was not one that should have been new to them, because it had been communicated clearly to them.
defaultLord Bilimoria:default Is this what you see as a justification for a different outcome for your members when other partnerships—for example, in the agricultural sector, we have just heard—see the need to retain profits for business expansion?
defaultPaul Haledefault: This part of the schedule—the AIFM business—addresses a very particular problem, which is the cash flow and tax liability position of members of an AIFM business.
default 
defaultIt does not enable hedge fund managers to retain cash for working capital or to indulge in any other sort of scheme.
default 
defaultAs I said, it is not a tax-raising measure.
default 
defaultThe key point of the arrangement, which, I am afraid, the representative of the accountancy professions did not fully grasp, is that the tax on the variable remuneration can, if the business and the member elect to go within the scheme, because it is voluntary, be raised if the profits are deemed for tax purposes to be accruing to the business itself—the LLP—even though it is not a person for tax purposes.
default 
defaultThe LLP then has a tax liability on that amount equal to 45%, and the LLP pays that tax.
defaultWhen the profits vest in the partner in whom they are originally intended to go to
default,
default in perhaps three years’ time, that partner is treated at that point as receiving the gross amount of the profits, which includes a tax credit for that 45%.
default 
defaultThose profits are treated as arising to him as the profits of the trade in that later year of assessment.
default 
defaultThe amount of tax that he pays will then depend on what the tax rate is at that period.
default 
defaultIf we have a Government that has put it up to 50% from 45%, he suffers.
default 
defaultHe can also bring into account any reliefs like pension payments, gift aid or trading losses that are available.
default 
defaultSo, we have had a payment on account and then a realignment when the deferred profits adjust, and everybody, give or take the vagaries of life, is happy.
defaultIf the profits have not vested, then, from a tax point of view, that is it: the amount is treated as a capital sum.
default 
defaultIf it is reallocated by the LLP to other partners, they get it—a share of the 55 that is left out of the 100—and there is no further tax liability, but the tax credit that was paid on it cannot be recovered.
default 
defaultAgain, that reflects what the position is under current law: that, if a partnership, say, has retained an amount of money and not distributed it to its partners, the partners will have paid tax on that.
default 
defaultIf it then decides it does not need this money but will reallocate it
default to
default particular partners, they have no tax liability on it, because it is an amount of capital within that partnership.
default 
defaultThat is a very convenient and easy way of resolving the issue of how to deal with lost, unvested deferred remuneration.
default 
defaultIf you wanted to be more rigorous, as it were, and trace through the tax credit and see how the profits vest through into other partners who get this at second, third or fourth hand, remember the deferral periods of up to five years.
default 
defaultYou could have a paper trail going through various deferral rounds and taking you for 20 years, and that was not appealing to the industry or to the Revenue as an exercise.
