defaultQ65 default&#xa0; 
default 
defaultThe Chairman:default I wonder if I could ask one final question.
default 
defaultDo you think the Government does enough to monitor and evaluate whether the tax changes it has introduced meet their policy objectives, and if not, what more should they do?
default 
defaultPaul Haledefault: There are, perhaps, two different types of tax change here that need to be considered.
default 
defaultThe first, which is really what we have been talking about today, is anti-avoidance measures.
default 
defaultThose are effectively monitored, because HMRC has identified an abuse and told the Government it needs to be dealt with.
default 
defaultHaving introduced the legislation
default,
default they will continue to monitor tax returns, disclosures of tax schemes et cetera to try and determine whether it has been effective or not, so in that sense that monitoring is continuous.
default 
defaultSome form of public report to say, “Yes this has been successful; hey, look, we think we have saved 
default£
defaultX billion from being lost” may or may not be necessary.
defaultThe other sort of tax change out there is a measure that would be designed to influence behaviour, or encourage investment, or something like that.
default 
defaultThere is a much stronger case for having a more formal system for reviewing that.
default 
defaultPresumably, the Treasury does internally wish to know whether a measure that has been promoted has been successful.
default 
defaultPresumably, where it has been promoted at the behest of an interested body, they will be monitoring it.
default 
defaultSo, if you have some sort of relief for building wind farms or producing films in the UK, interest groups will be getting input from their members as to whether it is working or not.
default 
defaultNow, there is always going to be a time lag in finding out how effective something like that is, because tax returns come in, say, a year after the profits have been earned against which the relief is being claimed, and then they are considered.
default 
defaultYou are always going to have a timescale of two or three years before the results are known.
default 
defaultHowever, presumably, if a measure has been introduced for a policy reason like that, then there should be a mechanism of evaluating whether it has been successful.
default 
defaultIt would be interesting for the general public to know whether the relief has been put to good use or not.
default 
default 
defaultQ66 default&#xa0; 
default 
defaultBaroness Drake:default I will try to make this very brief.
default 
defaultMr Hale, of the three economic tests—variable profits, influence over management and capital contribution—which will pose the greatest challenge to your members?
default 
defaultPaul Haledefault: To go in reverse order, as it were, the capital test is very likely to be of absolutely no help.
default 
defaultHedge fund management businesses, because they do not hold client money, and as I said at the beginning, because they are not trading their own assets, have a very low regulatory capital requirement.
default 
defaultIt may be something like 13 weeks’ expenses.
default 
defaultIf things go well in a hedge fund, the financial rewards are very great and the variable remuneration therefore could well be expected to be more than four times the amount of capital that the individual has put in.
default 
defaultThe variable remuneration, in some businesses, would be an issue.
default 
defaultIt is not quite clear how that is defined and operated in practice. There is, as drafted, a definite link to the overall profits of the business.
default 
defaultIn a lot of businesses, you will have people who are remunerated, to some extent, by the results of their own income stream.
default 
defaultThe accountancy bodies touched on that earlier.
default 
defaultHowever, you could well have a situation in a fund management business where you have, perhaps, three funds and three separate teams that are largely responsible for each fund.
default 
defaultTheir remuneration will be tailored to those particular funds’ performance, rather than to the performance of the business as a whole.
default 
defaultNow, you may be able to come up with an arrangement in your partnership agreement that says your remuneration will be assessed by looking at the profits of the business as a whole, and deciding what proportion of that profit you will get in terms of performance units.
default 
defaultPerformance units will be geared to what you have done in your own part of the business.
default 
defaultIs that getting close enough to the parties being affected substantially by the whole profits of the business or not?
default 
defaultI do not know.
default 
defaultThe draft guidance the Revenue has published is not particularly helpful on that point.
default 
defaultThen, finally, there is significant influence.
default 
defaultIt is clear that significant influence does not mean the abi
defaultlity to control the business; it means the ability to make your voice heard and have your opinions taken into account.
default 
defaultThe Revenue suggest in their guidance that if you have a management board of 10 they would regard, in principle, all of those 10 as having significant influence.
default 
defaultIf you have more than 10 on the board, some of those people would not have significant influence.
default 
defaultThat characteristic is going to be one that will help clarify the position of a lot of members in hedge fund management businesses, because—and again, I do not have the figures on this—my experience is that a lot of the businesses are 10 partners or less.
default 
defaultHowever, there will be some businesses where you have a large number of partners and/or distinct income or profit streams within the business, where there will be more of an issue.
default 
